^0^Changing Your Password
^$10
Changing Your Password

Use Password to change your user account password.

To change your password, do the following:

Note: If you are already in the Preferences folder, go to Step 2.

1.\t\d(Double-click^double-click) on Preferences in the \k("UnixWare Desktop" window^DesktopMgr/desktop.hlp^The UnixWare Desktop Window).

2.\tDouble-click on Password. The "Password" window appears, prompting you
  \tto enter your old password.

3.\tType in your old password and press Enter. The system prompts
  \tyou for a new password (see \k(Rules for Creating Passwords)).

4.\tThe system prompts you to enter the new password again. Type in the
  \tnew password and press Enter.

  \tNote: If the password does not match the new password, the system
  \tprompts you to try again.

5.\tThe "Password" window disappears. Your new password is now in effect.  

^1^Rules for Creating Passwords
^$20
Rules for Creating Passwords

When you create a password for your login account, it must meet the
following requirements:

\to\tThe password must have between six and eight characters (the system
\t \tignores any characters over eight.

\to\tThe password must contain at least two alphabetic characters and at
\t \tleast one numeric or special character (*, %, @, and so forth). You can
\t \tuse either uppercase or lowercase characters.

\t \tRemember to type them in at login time exactly as you created them.
\t \tThat is, if you created the password as ABC123, you must enter
\t \tuppercase ABC when you log in. If you try to use abc123, the system
\t \twill not accept it.

\to\tThe password must differ from your login name. 

\to\tA new password must differ from your old password by at least three
\t \tcharacters.

See also:
